


     1.0  HISTORY AND MOTIVATION

     The VMOVPG UUO was originally intended as an aid to cut down on the
     amount of I/O necessary to output a new page of data to a file.  It
     is also useful in transferring a page  from  one  file  to  another
     file,  or  taking the contents of a private page and cause it to be
     mappable from a file.

     Without VMOVPG, it took at least 3, possibly 4,  pages  of  I/O  to
     write  a  new  page  to  a  file.   When  a  new disk page is first
     allocated, that page has whatever contents the previous user of the
     page left there.  Before that page is put into a file RIB, the page
     must either be zeroed, or new contents must  be  written  onto  the
     disk  page.   If  this is not done and the system crashes after the
     disk page address is put into the RIB slot, the file's  owner  will
     see  the  old disk page user's data, which is a security violation.
     For this reason, FCREAT CHANIO zeroes the disk page and  waits  for
     the I/O to complete before putting the disk page's address into the
     RIB.  This causes 2 I/O cycles - one to read in the page (there  is
     no  mode in the current paging system to map in a page and not read
     in the contents when it is referenced) and one to write the  zeroes
     out.   When  the  user of the file page maps in the page and writes
     his new data, there may be another disk read, and certainly will be
     another  write  when  he removes the page, making 3 or 4 I/O cycles
     all together.

     The solution of inventing a RIB pointer bit  which  says  the  page
     hasn't  been  written  out yet (virgin file page) doesn't eliminate
     the I/O, since an extra RIB read/write would be necessary to  clear
     the  bit  after  the new disk page had its initial contents written
     out.

     It has always been true that private pages are  not  read  in  when
     they are first created.  There is a state for a private page called
     "virgin", which the system uses to recognize that  the  page  is  a
     freshly  created  private  page  which  doesn't  need to be read in
     before being written into.  After the page is written, the physical
     core  page  becomes  dirty,  and is written out if the core page is
     reclaimed.

     The VMOVPG UUO allows such a private page to become mappable from a
     file.   This  way, only 1 I/O operation is necessary to write a new
     page of data into a file.  The user  creates  a  private  page  and
     writes the data into it (no need to worry about RIBS yet since page
     is private), and does the VMOVPG UUO to cause the private  page  to
     turn  into  a  page  which can be mapped from the target file.  The
     VMOVPG UUO must ensure that the new data in the page is written out
     to  the  disk  before  making  the  page  part  of the file for the
     security reason outlined above.   The  page  can  then  be  further
     referenced  by  the  program,  or  VREMOVed  if  the program has no
     further need to reference the page.
