     2.0  VMOVPG UUO LOGIC.

     2.1  KMOVPG

     The  kernel  for  the  KMOVPG  UUO  follows  the  general   calling
     conventions for paging UUO kernel routines (F/DDB, T1,T2/arguments)
     First, the arguments are moved into other ACs and checked.  -1  for
     a  file  page  indicates  the page position right after the current
     (instantaneous) end of file.

     The page slot is checked to make sure it exists and is not a  super
     slot.

     If the page is a private virgin page, it is referenced  to  get  it
     out  of that state, since a validating a virgin page will not write
     anything out to the disk.

     For all pages in the specified range, if the page is  private,  the
     UUO routine for validate start is called for it, with a special bit
     that tells validate to write the page out even  if  it  is  private
     (normally  validates  of  private pages are noops.) This is done so
     that whatever I/O needs to be done can be started all at once while
     the UUO is running.

     The next phase sets up the file to make sure it is ready to get the
     new  page  or pages.  The DELXCH routine is called, which locks the
     file for read and returns the current  highest  page  written(HPW).
     SETACH  is  called  to  indicate  that  the  file's  allocation  is
     changing, so that in the event of  a  crash  before  the  PCBs  are
     written out, DSKCLN will notice that file when running in fast mode
     and include its pages in the SATs.

     If any of the pages to be inserted are  past  the  current  highest
     page  written,  new  RIB  slots must be used, which may necessitate
     changing from the current number of RIBs to a new number  of  RIBs.
     So,  if  the  file  isn't  append  only, the routine LOKHPW must be
     called to get the atomic file lock for write.  LOKHPW  reschedules,
     so  it  must  make sure someone else didn't sneak in and change the
     HPW, or discover that the RIB was bad.  It is possible  that  after
     getting  the  atomic  file  lock  for  write that the file has been
     extended by another frame so that it  now  includes  all  the  file
     position  slots  that  are  needed.   If  this  is the case, LOKHPW
     returns T1 negative, and the code that  extends  the  file  out  is
     skipped.

     If LOKHPW returns indicating  that  the  file  still  needs  to  be
     extended,  the  write  lock is now in possession of the frame.  The
     append only check is  applied,  and  if  it  passes,  the  file  is
     extended  with  HOLES  by  the  new  routine  SWEPRH.   Since it is
     possible for the caller to indicate that the first page  to  insert
     into the file is one or more pages past the first non-existent file
     page past the end of file, doing VMOVPG can result  in  REAL  HOLES
     showing  up in the file.  The alternative to this was to complicate
     the code by calling SWEPHO to fill in pages up to the first page to
     insert,  and  then  calling SWEPRH to make real holes to insert the
                                                                  Page 3


     new pages.  Since the TITO crock is a crock and will  go  away,  it
     was  my feeling to do this UUO and just let the caller beware if he
     doesn't want to create real holes, by  calling  it  with  arguments
     starting  only on existing file pages or starting at the first page
     past the current EOF.

     SWEPRH may get the rib, and we still have  to  validate  pages  and
     reschedule,  so  we call RELRIB to release the RIB.  A tricky thing
     to watch when debugging and writing these file system UUOs is  that
     because  of  the  DDB  pointers,  sometimes  the  RIB is gotten and
     sometimes it is not.  So if you forget to release it and your  test
     case  only  causes pointers to come from or go to DDB pointer area,
     you may never find out until too  late  that  you  forgot  to  call
     RELRIB.

     At KMOVNH we setup W and M again to get ready  to  go  through  the
     main   loop  for  each  page  in  the  argument  range.   First,  a
     validate/wait is done to make sure the page (which was started  out
     above), if it is private, has now been written onto the disk.

     Next, we check the quota for the file's directory to make  sure  it
     has not been exceeded.  If GETB is on, this check is skipped.  This
     is there so when SIMIO gets adapted to use VMOVPG to write new file
     pages out, it can do its own quota checking.  The thing I wanted to
     avoid in SIMIO is to have 3 SIMIO output UUOs succeed, and then the
     fourth  one  that  causes the VMOVPG to get done get the over quota
     return, in which case the 3 outputs that seemed  to  succeed  never
     got their data into the file.

     Next, we call USETST to cause DEVRET(F) to point to the DDB pointer
     area  where  the  page  whose  number  is  in  AC  M  can be found.
     Originally, I used a routine called DELCRE, which got the RIB  even
     if  the  DDB  pointer  area had the desired page, but it turned out
     that this slowed VMOVPG down considerably.  In the original version
     of  VMOVPG  I  followed the example of FCREAT and wrote the pointer
     into the DDB and the RIB slot.  This caused the RIB to get  written
     out  for  each page added to the file.  Changing the call to USETST
     made it so the RIB doesn't get updated from the  DDB  pointer  area
     until  it  absolutely has to, which may be as late as when the file
     is closed.  This has the  disadvantage,  however,  of  opening  the
     window during which the system can crash and the pages added to the
     file are lost.  Since MAGNUM does RIB validates to prevent this,  I
     didn't consider this disadvantage serious.

     If the file position in question is already a real page, the  error
     return  is  given.  There is no effort to undo any work done to the
     file for previous pages in this VMOVPG call.

     Next, the SAT is gotten into a PCB completely locked.  The complete
     lock is necessary as an interlock on the disk page, to make sure no
     one else creates or deletes a shared page table entry for  it.   If
     the disk address the user is trying to insert into the file has the
     F bit set (the page is already in a file) we give the error return.
     Note  we can't just check to see if the page's ATB is a file rather
     than dummy (private) ATB, because the UUO allows a page which  used
                                                                  Page 4


     to  be  mappable  from  a  file and has since been deleted from the
     file's RIB to be inserted into a new file.  Deleted file pages that
     are  still  mapped  are still connected to the old file via the old
     file's ATB.

     This brings us to label KMOV3N.  We want to make sure  the  virtual
     page  in  question  is not shared.  If it is, since we are going to
     switch ATBs for the page, we need to know if the  page  is  shared.
     We  don't  want  to  give  an error return just because the page is
     shared, because someone  might  be  examining  the  frames  address
     space,  which  uses  replicates  and causes pages to be shared.  It
     would be unfortunate for the UUO to fail just because  someone  was
     looking  around  at  the  frame.   I  also judged it undesirable to
     complicate the SPT structure by having to link old  SPTs  with  new
     SPTs, which would have to be done if the page remained shared after
     it moved to the new file.  The problem was that LMAP slots  contain
     SPT  addresses,  and  after  the page was moved to the new file all
     LMAP slots for  that  disk  page  would  have  to  have  their  SPT
     addresses  updated  sooner  or later.  This would require a pointer
     from the old SPT slot to the new SPT slot.  Rather than do this,  I
     decided to take the easy way out by remembering the old protection,
     changing the protectionto copy on write, doing a SETMM, causing the
     page  to become private.  This happens at KMVMKP if the page has an
     SPT number with a share count greater than 1.  Note all  locks  are
     released  before  doing  this, as the SETMM could reschedule.  Also
     note that routine VPADR sets up  PC.UIO  so  that  the  SETMM  will
     reference the proper address space.  Note that this means all other
     sharers of the page will be sharing the page as it used  to  exist,
     and  the  VMOVPG  caller  actually  gets another page with the same
     data.

     After this is done, we can now the the F bit in the sat.  We didn't
     want  to  set  it  until  after  all  possible  error  returns were
     encountered, or else it would be possible to call the UUO in such a
     way as to result in a lost page.

     We set the virtual pages disk address into the DDB area, set PTRCHG
     because  we  have written into the pointer area, and call ONESLT to
     find and update all other DDBs which include  the  pointer  we  are
     updating.   After  this, we call RELRIB in case USETST had to get a
     RIB.  We update the file size and DRB with routine UPDAC0.

     Now the disk data base is taken care of.  We now  must  switch  the
     slot  to the new ATB.  Since we still have the SAT write locked, we
     know the  page  can't  change  mapping  state  (e.g.   no  one  can
     replicate  it,  or  map  it  from  the new file that we just put it
     into).  First, we call DECUNS to  disconnect  this  slot  from  its
     current  ATB.   The slot may or may not be in shared format, and it
     may be unshared format  and  have  an  SPT  entry  left  somewhere.
     DECUNS  decrements the unshared map count (ATBUMC), max write cound
     (ATBMXW), clears the max write count up bit (ATPMXU).  If the  slot
     is  discovered  to  be  truly  shared  (SPT use count equal to 2 or
     greater) the error return is given.  This should never happen.

     Now, we call the routine INCUMC (used by MAPKRN too) which  is  the
                                                                  Page 5


     normal  way to inform an ATB of the presence of another page mapped
     from its file.  We have  to  increment  the  max  write  count  (if
     appropriate) ourselves, since INCUMC doesn't do it for us.

     Now, all that remains is to set the new ATB address into the target
     VP's  LMAP  slot.  This may result in the slot going from shared to
     unshared.  DECUNS turned the shared bit off if  it  was  on.   Note
     that  routine GETLMA was used to get the LMAP slot this time, since
     we are not just taking a peek  at  it  but  untend  to  change  its
     contents)  The  ATB/SPT  fields  for  the core page, if the slot is
     active, also need to be updated.  PGYSPT is zeroed, since there are
     no  more  sharer's of the page.  (If there was an SPT entry for the
     page, it has been deleted by DECUNS).  The LMAP slot is stored, and
     the  SAT  is finally released.  The atomic file lock is still kept,
     since the DDB pointers are still going to be read and written.

     At the end of the loop,  the  atomic  file  lock  is  released  the
     routine returns.

     Note that none of the code after the SAT is  obtained  reschedules,
     so  the SAT is kept for the minimum amount of time.  Also note that
     the canonical order for interlocks is followed:  Context page lock,
     atomic file lock, RIB, SAT, CB (DECUNS uses CB).



     2.2  SWEPPG Use Of VMOVPG

     MAPIO has  been  changed  to  use  VMOVPG  instead  of  its  normal
     function.   At  SWEEP2,  it  checks  to see if the sweep routine is
     doing real pages and only 1 page.  By the time we  get  to  SWEEP2,
     the  file  has been extended if it needs to be, so if we're doing 1
     real page, it will wind up at the  first  page  past  highest  page
     written.   We release all the locks and resources we could possibly
     have, and VCREAT a single page and insert it into the file  at  HPW
     with  VMOVPG.   This  avoids  having to call CREPAG, which does the
     page create the old way.  If VMOVPG gets any errors, the same error
     code will be passed up to the caller.  If any problems come up that
     you suspect are due to this change, its easy to make the code  what
     it  used to do by patching the test instruction at SWEEP2 to always
     go to SWEP2A.  Note that if the file has to be extended, it is done
     the old way with CREPAG.  It is not done with VMOVPG because VMOVPG
     leaves holes in the file between HPW and the page just  before  the
     one  to  be  inserted.   It would be very inefficient to VMOVPG one
     page per call to extend the file, compared to what SWEPPG does, and
     VMOVPG  doesn't  have more than 1 virtual page (%COW) to work with,
     so it couldn't insert many pages at once.
