     2.3  SIMIO Use Of VMOVPG

     I didn't get to really research what exactly needs to  be  done  to
     SIMIO to take advantage of VMOVPG, but I have a general idea.  When
     SIMIO gets the "past HPW" error return when mapping a page from the
     file  its  doing output to, it now FCREATes a new page, maps it in,
     and then BLTs the user's data to it.  SIMIO doesn't remove the page
     immediately,  since  later  buffers  output need to BLT data to the
     same page.  What would be involved to use VMOVPG would be to VCREAT
     a  page  instead of FCREAT and MAP.  The user's data would be BLTed
     in as usual.  A new flag for every virtual page SIMIO uses would be
     created  to indicate that this page is private (or you could take a
     short cut and just check the LMAP slot to see  if  its  private  or
     not).   Theoretically,  SIMIO  was  supposed to be able to run as a
     user program, so has as few direct calls to monitor subroutines  as
     possible,  but  practically speaking, UUOs were not created for all
     SIMIO functions that needed to be done and there are  quite  a  few
     kludges in the file system torecognize that SIMIO is doing the call
     and the file size is set differently than otherwise would be.   So,
     when  SIMIO  goes  to  remove  the  page,  it sees that the page is
     private, and does a VMOVPG to insert the private page into the file
     at the HPW.

     Some details have to be worked out with regard to  the  disk  quota
     and  what  we guarantee will get actually get out to the disk after
     an OUT or OUTPUT UUO.  With the disk quota, its not  acceptable  to
     allow  the  user 3 successful outputs and have the 4th fail because
     he went over quota and VMOVPG didn't let him  actually  insert  the
     page  into  the  file,  resulting  in  the  loss  of the 3 previous
     outputs.  So what needs to be done is  for  SIMIO  to  do  its  own
 heck.   VMOVPG  will  skip  the  quota check if the caller is exec
     mode, so all exec mde callers are responsible for quota checking.

     I am a little concerned about the safety factor,  too.   Currently,
     the  number of free pages is set to be lower than the actual number
     of free pages, so that in case the disk fills entirely, people  can
     still  run  programs  (creating  private  pages)  to  be able to do
     something about obtaining disk space.  If  SIMIO  uses  VMOVPG,  it
     circumvents  this  mechanism.   So even if the STRTAL word is zero,
     the system still allows the users to create  private  pages,  which
     can  then  be  inserted into files, circumventing the normal safety
     factor.  A possible solution for  VMOVPG  not  to  allow  inserting
     private  pages into files if STRTAL is zero.  This restriction need
     not apply to pages that are not private and no longer mappable from
     a file.

     Currently, SIMIO guarantees that dump mode OUTPUT UUOs write  their
     data  onto  the  disk  immediately  by doing validates on the page.
     This is to simulate the old behavior of the system in case  current
     applications were counting on this behavior.  SIMIO doesn't do this
     for buffered mode, since the old system made no  guarantees  as  to
     whether  or  not  the  data got out to disk after successful return
     from an buffered OUTPUT UUO.  If SIMIO is converted to use  VMOVPG,
     it looks like we will have to give this compatibility up, since the
     data being OUTPUT won't even get into the file until the next  page
                                                                  Page 7


     is  needed  to be mapped from the file or the file is closed.  Care
     will need to be taken  that  in  all  cases  where  SIMIO  formerly
     removed a virtual page, the page is checked to make sure that if it
     is private a VMOVPG is done to insert it into the file.  It  looked
     pretty  easy  to  do,  since  there  is  only one place where SIMIO
     removes those pages, routine SIMRMV.
